<br>
1) There is NO difference between Song Haste and Spell Haste when it comes to the stacking rules.<br>
<br>
2) You can have ONE Haste Item and ONE Spell/Song Haste stack, period.<br>
<br>
Example:  <br>
--------<br>
Our Monk named 'Max Hasted' has the following gear:<br>
<br>
Celestial Fists (41% Song Haste aste when right clicked)<br>
FBSS (21% Haste Item)<br>
<br>
He also has a Epiced enchanter 'Mezzin' Fewl' friend who can give him 'Speed of the Shissar' (70% Spell Haste).<br>
<br>
<br>
So, Max Hasted goes to engage 'An Uber MOB 01'.  He hits auto attack and right clicks his epic. At this point his haste percentage is:<br>
<br>
FBSS (21% Item) + Epic (41% Song) = 62%<br>
<br>
now, 'Mezzin' Fewl' looks up from his Gems screen to see our Monk engaged. He dicides to givie the Monk 'Speed of the Shissar' as our Monk right clicks his Epic again.  At this point, with EQ's Haste Stacking Rules, our Monk's Haste Percentage is:<br>
<br>
<br>
FBSS (21% Item) + Epic (41% Song) + Speed of Shissar (70% Spell) = 91%<br>
<br>
Hey, wait a minute! Why is the Haste Percentage only 91% and not 161%?<br>
<br>
That's because you can onlt have ONE Haste Item and the HIGHER Percentage of any Song/Spell buff stack REGARDLESS of whether you see more than one Haste Song/Spell icon in your buff window at the same time.<br>
<br>
So, since the 'Speed of the Shissar' Haste (70%) is higher that the Monk Epic Haste (41%); the Monk Epic Haste component is overwritten by the 'Speed of the Shissar' Haste component.<br>
<br>
However, here's why having the Monk Epic (or RotWF effect) up ISN'T a waste in the above situation:<br>
<br>
While the Haste component won't stack, the OTHER components will (ie you still get the +50 ATK and +12 AC from the Monk Epic, and/or the +STR and other stuff from the RotWF while they're active).<br>
<br>
<br>
Lastly, there are TWO Bard Songs and ONE Monk discipline that DO NOT adhere to the above stacking rules, but that's it.  Other than that, the stack of Item/Spell/Song haste works as described above.<br>
<br>
